node.text: In our latest edition of “On Location,” we’re thrilled to showcase the new home collection (@sirianointeriors) by award-winning fashion designer and CFDA member Christian Siriano (@csiriano), which is debuting exclusively on 1stDibs. He takes us into his “dusty but fabulous” studio for a behind-the-scenes peek at his beautifully crafted work. As with his statement-making clothes, Christian’s furniture designs all start with a sketch and are inspired by everything from candy (see the gumdrop stool) to old movies and picnics in the park. Click the link in bio to shop the chic, sartorially-inspired collection.

node.text: Join us for a new edition of “On Location,” in which we visit fine art embroiderer @richardsaja in his Catskill, NY, studio. Richard’s work is a kind of meditation in which time evaporates in a blur of color and stitching. He transforms classical mediums—toile fabrics and tapestries—with what he refers to as “historical inaccuracy.” Surrounded by a rainbow palette of embroidery floss, he takes a coloring book approach to pastoral scenes. They emerge infused with contemporary issues and cultural memes that celebrate difference and encourage tolerance. Click the link in bio to discover more of Richard’s enchanting embroidered, decorative, graphic and fine art pieces.

node.title: On Location With Fine Art Embroiderer Richard Saja

node.text: In the past few years, Hudson, NY, has gone from “destination-on-the-rise” to full-blown hot spot. Paris Grant (@miss_parisg), head of interiors at @reddymadedesign in New York City, dons a chic lace mask and takes us on a whirlwind tour of some of this upstate town’s incredible array of antiques shops and design galleries. Like a kid in a candy store, she displays an infectious enthusiasm for the many treasures on display. Click the link in bio to read more in Introspective. 🎥: @harry_zernike

node.title: In Hudson, Decorator Paris Grant Takes Us on a Hunt for Design Treasures

node.text: Is an engagement ring from the Victorian era (1837-1901) calling your name? These feminine designs often feature small rose cut or old mine cut diamonds, along with ornate patterns hammered into the gold settings. Romantic motifs include hearts, flowers and stars, but the swirling two-stone toi et moi rings are perhaps the ultimate symbol of an eternal bond. Click the link in bio to watch the full video on shopping for vintage or antique rings.

node.title: Victorian, Edwardian and Art Deco Rings on 1stDibs

node.text: Our latest edition of “On Location: Personal Space” takes us into the light-drenched Brooklyn duplex of Milan-born designer Mario Milana and his wife, the Colombian actress Gabriella Campagna. Their home beautifully embodies the same mix of warm, organic elements and refined geometries found in Mario’s work. His simple and efficient morning routine sets him up for a quarantine day of painting, reading, soaking up sunshine in the back garden and more meditation—seated in his low-slung Asana chair, of course!

node.title: On Location with 1stdibs maker Mario Milana

node.text: Next up in our new series, “On Location: Personal Space,” we spend a little time with potter, designer and author @jonathanadler. Where better to shelter in place alongside his husband—writer and fashion icon (and videographer!) @simondoonan— and their dog Foxy than the gorgeous home they share on Shelter Island? With its bright palette, groovy furnishings and sweeping ocean views, it’s the ideal place to work and play. Surrounded by his own creations and collections, Jonathan is managing to drink tea, practice his pull-ups and do a lot of reading.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by 1stDibs on August 08, 2021 tagging @davidaaronarts. May be an image of sculpture.

node.text:
This exceptionally fine bronze cat, dating from around the 5th century B.C., highlights the Egyptian mastery of metallurgy as well as the rich vocabulary of animal motifs in ancient Egyptian art. A cat very similar to this one, found in the collection of the Louvre Museum in Paris, provides an idea of the ritualistic use of these statues. The hieroglyphic inscription tells of a certain Mersopdu, son of Hor, who made a temple offering of the statue during the Late Dynasty, now regarded by scholars as the last great flowering of native Egyptian culture. Click the link in bio to get a closer look in honor of #InternationalCatDay. 📸:
@davidaaronarts

node.text: For Juniper House, a 4-bedroom waterfront home in Sydney, Dylan and Nicolette Farell of @dylan_farrell_design—native New Yorkers currently practicing internationally out of Australia—were challenged to create an audacious “surprise” home for the homeowner and his future bride. They envisioned a sense of atmospheric calm, highlighted by prismatic pops of color and plenty of texture. Much of the furniture and lighting was designed by Dylan and crafted by local artisans, with the remaining elements chosen for their lyricism and romance. Click the link in bio to explore more from the design firm. 📸: @felix_forest

node.text: Today is the birthday of Andy Warhol (1928-1987), the King of Pop Art. From his beginnings as a commercial illustrator to his forays into printmaking, photography, silkscreening, filmmaking and publishing, this versatile artist made an indelible impression on the culture. Celebrated to this day, Warhol remains one of the most important artists of the 20th century and continues to influence contemporary creators. Click the link in bio to discover a world of Warhol. 📸: @shaperomodern

node.text: Studio-Chacha (@studio_chacha.kr), based in Seoul, Korea, seeks to combine unfamiliar elements with familiar ones in order to come up with a new aesthetic. With a current focus on glass, the studio has introduced this set of sculpted coffee tables made of dichroic glass, produced by stacking layers of glass with micro-layers of metals or oxides that display shifting colors depending on the angle of view. The result is ethereal and mesmerizing. 📸: @galerie.philia

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by 1stDibs on August 04, 2021 tagging @kitkempdesignthread. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text: In addition to her residential commissions, British interior designer @kitkempdesignthread created the celebrated interiors for her ten Firmdale Hotels, in London and New York. Known for spinning immersive worlds, she always begins with what she calls the five Cs: character, color, comfort, craft and curation. In her new book, “Design Secrets,” Kemp reveals her tricks for adding a dose of wizardry to a room, including the playful layering of bold patterns, bright colors, whimsical artworks and handcrafted objects. See more of this compelling designer’s work in our Introspective feature. 📸: @simonbrownphotography @wheresbrentbeen

node.text: For her Lunar Chair, Slovenian designer @larabohinc found inspiration in the trajectories of heavenly bodies, whose gravitationally curved trajectories drive the elegant lines and delicate, minimal shapes. Entirely handmade of thin square rods in brushed brass and upholstered in Dedar bouclé, the chair has two enveloping crescents for armrests and a smaller backrest which, like a moon, circles its planet on an orbit of its own. Click the link in bio to discover more. 📸: @bohincstudio

node.text:
Charged with creating a London version of a longstanding client’s Palm Beach home, @studioverouk started with a palette of neutrals offset with hues of blue and green. The brilliant blue door of the architecturally stunning white stucco villa opens onto a bright space with a sense of modern grandeur. The living room is anchored by a Victorian carved statuary marble fireplace purchased at auction and a black lacquered wood coffee table from the 1940s by Gerard Mille. Click the link in bio to explore more. 📸:
@andreasvoneinsiedel

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by 1stDibs on August 01, 2021 tagging @derrickadamsny, and @msfineart55. May be an illustration of one or more people.

node.text: Derrick Adams (@derrickadamsny) is an artist whose work, centered around his identity, frequently references patterns, images, and themes of Black culture in America. His multidisciplinary practice spans painting, collage, sculpture, performance, video and sound installations to explore questions of how African American experiences intersect with art history, American iconography and consumerism. Adams’ tendency to layer, hybridize and collage not only images and materials, but also different types of sensory experiences, links him to an estimable lineage of pioneers ranging from Hannah Höch and Henri Matisse to William H. Johnson and Romare Bearden. Click the link in bio to discover more from the artist. 📸: @msfineart55

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by 1stDibs in London, United Kingdom with @studioduggan. May be an image of indoor.

node.text: For this Arts & Crafts-era family home in North London’s Hampstead Heath, @studioduggan chose a rich, grounding palette of pink, tan and mustard tones. Lime paint, terrazzo flooring and cane were used extensively to breathe new life into this period property. In the bathroom, @farrowandball’s Red Earth complements curtains made from Soane’s Kalamkari Chevron fabric. The oak stool is antique (circa 1870) and the artwork by Lumitrix lends a contemporary touch. Click the link in bio to see more of the home. 📸: @mariell.lindhansen

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by 1stDibs on July 30, 2021. May be an image of furniture.

node.text: Ettore Sottsass (1917-2007) originally became known as a designer with Olivetti, where, through color, form and styling, he brought office equipment into the realm of popular culture. During the ‘80s, as the Memphis movement rose to prominence, he opened his own design consultancy, primarily an architectural practice, but also responsible for the creation of identities, interiors and furniture of all kinds. Sottsass designed this supremely modern, Piccoli Libri Cabinet in 1992. It’s one from a limited edition made of plastic-laminate-covered maple-veneered wood and metal. Click the link in bio to shop this piece and more from the iconic designer. 📸: DADA

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by 1stDibs in New Jersey with @michellegersoninteriors. May be an image of table and indoor.

node.text: What designer isn’t a little house-proud? #1stDibs50 designer @michellegersoninteriors calls her own home in New Jersey “a jumble of loveliness,” but this dining room, while indeed lovely, is most definitely not a jumble. Like an orchestral score, the room brings order to a rich range of voices, from Moroccan pottery and vintage chairs sourced on 1stDibs to Apparatus Studio Lariat pendant lights and a lyrical six-panel screen. The last, a Japanese antique, was a gift from her mother, a piece Gerson had always admired growing up. “One day, I told her it would look a lot better in my house — and she said, ‘You’re right,’ and gave it to me!” Reason to be house-proud, for sure. Click the link in bio to see more from this year’s 1stDibs 50. 📸: @marcoriccastudio

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by 1stDibs on July 28, 2021 tagging @studioschalling. May be an image of chandelier.

node.text: Born in Helsinki, Finland, Paavo Tynell (1890-1973) began as a blacksmith and studied to become a master craftsman before co-founding Oy Taito Ab, a metalwork and lighting company. After focusing on statues and railings, they turned to the production of lamps and, ultimately, collaborated with distinguished designers and architects, such as Alvar Aalto and Kaj Franck. Tynell was known for elegant combinations of brass and glass, often decorated with perforated patterns, like this fine ceiling lamp from the 1950s. Click the link in bio to explore more of his timeless designs. 📸: @studioschalling
